<dl id="n12135b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12135b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12135b"> 135(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">+</font> 5 ft high / particoloured <font face="wake">+</font> / ass (relics) / wooden stirrups / bodyguard of planks</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Mais toute l&apos;attention se concentre sur ma&icirc;tre Vincent. Lui, vieux, les traits tir&eacute;s, il monte son petit &acirc;ne. Son habit est grossier, us&eacute;, rapi&eacute;c&eacute;, jadis blanc, devenu sale et poussi&eacute;reux. Sa monture est mis&eacute;rable, avec une sell des plus vulgaires et des &eacute;triers de bois suspendus &agrave;des cordes. <p>Tout cela se distingue &agrave;peine &agrave;travers le remuement de la foule. On ne voit gu&egrave;re que son bras droit tendu, qui dresse au-dessus des t&ecirc;tes, bien haute, une croix longue de cinq pieds, croix au Christ espagnol tordu et grima&ccedil;ant, peinturlur&eacute; de couleurs vives, &eacute;carlates, criardes. Souvent la foule en <font color="green">[85]</font> d&eacute;lire se pr&eacute;cipite sur lui pour faire des rel-iques de ses habits ou du poil de son &acirc;ne. Le ma&icirc;tre a horreur de ces exc&egrave;s qu&apos;il con-sid&egrave;re comme un sacril&egrave;ge. Il s&apos;en plaint avec amertume. Aussi, pour &eacute;viter cet in-conv&eacute;nient, de solides gaillards l&apos;entourent, porteurs d&apos;une v&eacute;ritable palissade mouvante de pieux carr&eacute;s, gros et hauts.</p> <br><font color="green">[But everybody&apos;s attention is focused on master Vincent. Old, haggard, he mounts his little ass. His coat is rough, worn, patched, once white, now dirty and dusty. His mount is miserable, with a most vulgar saddle and <mark>wooden stirrups</mark> hanging from ropes. / All this is hardly noticeable in the commotion of the crowd. You can only see his out-stretched right arm, waving <mark>a cross, five feet long</mark>, high over the heads, a cross with a Spanish, twisted and grimacing Christ, <mark>painted in bright colors, scarlet, showy</mark>. Often the delirious crowd [85]</font> jumps on him to make <mark>relics of his clothes or the hair of his donkey</mark>. The master hates these excesses which he considers sacrilegeous. He complains bitterly. So, to protect him against this inconvenience, <mark>muscular men surround him, carriers of a veritable moving fence of square planks</mark>, big and tall.] <small> Matthieu-Maxime Gorce, <a name="STVF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#STVF"><cite title="source">Saint Vincent Ferrier</cite></a> (1924) 85-86</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
